          "body": "The most theologically charged confrontations in the chapter's first half are not between Gideon and Midianites but between Gideon and fellow Israelites. Succoth and Penuel are Transjordanian Israelite cities — they are inside the covenant, not outside it. Their refusal to feed Gideon's weary army (8:5-9) is not merely cowardly pragmatism; it is a failure of covenantal solidarity with the LORD's appointed deliverer at the decisive moment of holy war. The hedge they make — 'are the hands of Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hand?' (8:6) — is the language of visible-evidence faith. They will not commit until the outcome is certain. Gideon's response is theologically grounded: he threatens punishment in the certainty of the LORD's coming victory ('when the LORD has given,' 8:7) and keeps his promises meticulously upon return (8:15-17). The punishment of Succoth (thorns and briers, 8:16) and Penuel (demolition and death, 8:17) is proportional escalation: the city that only taunted is disciplined; the city with a tower of military defiance is destroyed."
