          "body": "The chapter's political climax is Gideon's refusal of dynastic rule in verse 23: 'I will not rule over you, nor shall my son rule over you; the LORD shall rule over you.' Commentators from Calvin onward have noted the theological correctness of this statement — it is the only moment in the judges period where the theocratic principle is explicitly articulated in response to a monarchical offer. The problem is what immediately follows. Verse 24 opens with 'yet Gideon said to them' (the NASB's 'yet' translates a Hebrew waw-consecutive that signals both continuity and contrast). Before the crowd has dispersed, Gideon is collecting gold. Before his orthodox speech has echoed away, he is behaving like the king he just refused to be. He accumulates 1,700 shekels of gold (8:26), multiple wives and a concubine (8:30-31), and seventy sons — the royal harem scale of a Near Eastern monarch. As Swindoll observes in his Judges commentary, Gideon refused the title but took the perquisites. The pattern is the chapter's sharpest irony."
