          "body": "Verse 27 is the chapter's theological fulcrum: 'Gideon made it into an ephod, and placed it in his city, Ophrah, and all Israel played the harlot with it there, so that it became a snare to Gideon and his household.' Three observations are critical. First, the gold came from the spoils of a victory the LORD won — Gideon is melting divine provision into idolatrous material, precisely the pattern of Exodus 32:2-4 (the golden calf). The earring-collection scene (8:24-25) echoes Aaron's collection almost verbatim. Second, the ephod was not inherently an idol; it was a priestly instrument for inquiring of the LORD (cf. 1 Sam 23:9-12; 30:7-8). Installed in a hometown shrine rather than at the tabernacle, it becomes a substitute oracle — unauthorized mediation between God and Israel. Third, the narrator uses the covenant's standard idolatry-warning word (*moqesh*, snare) from Exodus 23:33 and Deuteronomy 7:16, where the Canaanite gods are called exactly this. Gideon's ephod has become functionally Canaanite. And the snare catches not just Israel — it catches Gideon's own household, the very household that chapter 9 will destroy."
