        "excerpt": "God has given the leaders of Midian, Oreb and Zeeb into your hands; and what was I able to do in comparison with you?",
        "body": "The chapter opens with a conflict that has nothing to do with Midian. The men of Ephraim are angry — not at the enemy, but at Gideon — for not including them in the initial muster (8:1). The complaint exposes a fault line that runs through the whole tribal period: honor-accounting displaces mission-accounting. Ephraim measures success by who was invited to participate, not by what the LORD accomplished. The tribe that carries the birthright blessing of Joseph (Gen 48:17-19) and will eventually house the tabernacle at Shiloh expects commensurate recognition in battle.\n\nGideon's response is a masterclass in diplomatic deflection. He does not argue about the original decision — he reframes the entire calculus. The 'gleaning of Ephraim' (their secondary capture of Oreb and Zeeb after the rout) is 'better than the vintage of Abiezer' (Gideon's own clan's initial harvest, 8:2). The comparison is deliberately self-diminishing, and it works: 'their anger toward him subsided when he said that' (8:3). The Hebrew word for 'subsided' (*raphah*) means to slacken, to go limp — the anger physically deflates.\n\nBut the narrator places this scene first for a reason. Gideon's diplomatic skill here will not reappear later. The man who manages Ephraim's wounded pride with patience will punish Succoth and Penuel with thorns and demolition. Wisdom and harshness are both present in this chapter; the chapter tracks when each is appropriate and when each becomes disproportionate. More importantly, Gideon's citation of God in verse 3 ('God has given...') will become increasingly rare as the chapter progresses. He begins by crediting the LORD; he ends building a shrine to himself.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Olelah* (gleanings, v.2) — the leftovers after the primary harvest, given to the poor in Mosaic law (Lev 19:10; Deut 24:21). That Gideon calls Ephraim's military prize the 'gleanings' and his own clan's work the 'vintage' is rhetorically clever — he simultaneously flatters Ephraim and subtly reverses the hierarchy (the 'gleaning' is called better than the 'vintage'). *Raphah* (subsided, v.3) — to slacken, grow limp; the same word used of the weakening of fear in Josh 1:9."
