        "excerpt": "Then Gideon and the 300 men who were with him came to the Jordan and crossed over, weary yet pursuing.",
        "body": "Verse 4 contains the chapter's most theologically resonant phrase: 'weary yet pursuing' (*ayeph ve-radaph*). Gideon and his 300 have already fought through the night rout of Midian (ch. 7), have called on Ephraim and Naphtali to close the escape routes (7:23-25), and have pursued the fleeing kings across the Jordan into deep Transjordanian wilderness. They are exhausted. And they are still moving. The pairing of *ayeph* (exhausted, faint) with the participle *radaph* (pursuing) — in the same clause, not in sequence — is the narrator's theological image for the posture of faith under hardship. Physical incapacity does not terminate covenantal obligation.\n\nThe towns of Succoth and Penuel refuse bread on the grounds of visible-evidence faith (8:6): they will not commit resources to an outcome they cannot yet see. Their logic is economically prudent and spiritually faithless. Gideon's response is not despair — he threatens specific, proportional punishment for specific, named officials (8:7, 8:9) and continues the pursuit. The threats are not bluster; verses 15-17 demonstrate that Gideon keeps every word he has spoken. He is a man of exact promises, which is both his military virtue and, later, the very quality that makes his accumulation of wives and wealth so deliberate.\n\nThe military campaign itself (8:10-12) is summarized with remarkable economy. 120,000 enemy swordsmen are already dead; 15,000 remain at Karkor. Gideon attacks by an unexpected route, 'when the camp was unsuspecting' (8:11) — the same tactical surprise that characterized the night raid of chapter 7. The capture of Zebah and Zalmunna is expressed in one verse (8:12): pursued, captured, routed. The narrator does not linger on the military feat. He is hurrying toward the more significant confrontation that follows.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ayeph* (weary/exhausted) appears twice in this passage (8:4, 5) — in v.4 describing the soldiers, in v.5 in Gideon's appeal to Succoth. The repetition emphasizes the physical reality of what the LORD's army is enduring. *Betach* (unsuspecting, v.11) — literally 'in trust/security,' the same word used of Laish in Judges 18:7 when the Danites attack it unawares. A secure camp is vulnerable to the unexpected approach."
