        "body": "The interrogation of Zebah and Zalmunna in verses 18-21 is the chapter's most psychologically complex scene, and the one most often read too simply. Gideon's question — 'what kind of men were they whom you killed at Tabor?' (8:18) — seems at first like a war-crimes inquiry. The answer reveals it is a blood-vengeance claim: the men killed at Tabor were Gideon's brothers, sons of his mother (8:19). The execution of Zebah and Zalmunna is therefore not simply the completion of holy war; it is personal. Gideon is acting as *goel* — the kinsman-avenger — whose covenantal right and duty to avenge the blood of a killed relative is codified in Numbers 35:19-21.\n\nThe scene's most searching dimension is the commission of Jether, Gideon's firstborn son (8:20). Gideon instructs the boy to kill the kings. The motive is honor: if a young man kills them, the kings die in shame; if Gideon himself must do it, he receives the honor but is not publicly vindicated as patriarch. Jether is afraid and does not draw his sword (8:20) — the text simply notes 'he was still a youth.' The kings themselves then demand Gideon perform the execution: 'as the man is, so is his strength' (8:21) — a proverb of warrior honor conceding that they wish to die by the hand of their equal, not a boy. Gideon executes them and takes the crescent ornaments from their camels' necks (8:21).\n\nThose crescent ornaments (*saharonim*) are not incidental detail. They reappear in verse 26 as part of the gold Gideon collects. The symbols of Midianite lunar religion — likely crescent moon pendants associated with the moon deity — will be incorporated into the material of Gideon's ephod. Holy war spoil, taken in the LORD's name, becomes the raw material of unauthorized worship. The sentence between military victory and religious failure is shorter than any reader anticipates.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Saharonim* (crescent ornaments, 8:21, 26) — from *sahar*, moon. The word appears only here and in Isaiah 3:18 (listed among the jewelry of Jerusalem's proud daughters). These are explicitly lunar religious symbols, making their incorporation into Gideon's ephod not merely aesthetic but syncretistic. *Goel* (kinsman-avenger) is not used in the text, but the legal framework of Numbers 35:19 is clearly operative — Gideon invokes the LORD's name as witness to the blood-oath (8:19)."
