        "body": "Verses 22-27 are the chapter's theological crisis, and they must be read as a single unit. Israel's offer of dynastic rule (8:22) is the first explicit monarchical proposal in Judges, anticipating Samuel's crisis in 1 Samuel 8. Gideon's refusal (8:23) is theologically correct and historically significant: 'the LORD shall rule over you' (*mashal*) names the theocratic principle that the entire covenant structure presupposes. No orthodox reader of the Pentateuch in the second millennium would miss the resonance — the LORD is Israel's king (Exod 15:18; Num 23:21; Deut 33:5).\n\nThe problem is the immediate sequel. The Hebrew waw-consecutive opening verse 24 connects the refusal and the request without pause: 'I will not rule over you...yet Gideon said to them, I would request of you.' The gold he collects — 1,700 shekels in earrings alone, plus crescent ornaments, pendants, purple robes, and neck chains (8:26) — amounts to a royal treasury. His seventy sons by many wives (8:30) and his concubine in Shechem (8:31) reflect the precise marital pattern Deuteronomy 17:17 prohibits for the king ('nor shall he multiply wives for himself'). Gideon refuses the name of king and acquires the substance of kingship: wealth, wives, and — in the ephod — cultic influence.\n\nThe ephod itself is the chapter's most contested object. Commentators from Peter Craigie to Daniel Block (NICOT, Judges) recognize that the priestly ephod was a legitimate instrument for divine inquiry (1 Sam 23:9-12). Gideon's error is installation: he places it in Ophrah, his hometown, rather than bringing it to the tabernacle. He creates a local oracle-shrine, usurping the Levitical priesthood's function. The result is that 'all Israel played the harlot with it there' (8:27) — the same covenant-infidelity language used for Baal worship. The snare (*moqesh*) catches not only Israel but Gideon's household — the very word Exodus 23:33 uses for the danger of leaving Canaanite gods in the land. Gideon has become the thing he was raised up to displace.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mashal* (rule/ruler, 8:22, 23 ×3) — the four uses in two verses concentrate the monarchical issue. *Moqesh* (snare, 8:27) — a trap; used in Exod 23:33, Deut 7:16 for Canaanite gods as snares to Israel; the narrator deliberately imports covenant-warning vocabulary here. *Zanah* (played the harlot, 8:27) — the standard prophetic metaphor for covenant infidelity, here applied to Gideon's artifact rather than to a foreign deity — which may be the narrator's point: the difference has collapsed."
