        "excerpt": "The sons of Israel did not remember the Lord their God, who had delivered them from the hands of all their enemies on every side.",
        "body": "The epilogue (8:28-35) is the chapter's most compressed and its most theologically damning passage. Verse 28 announces the military result (Midian subdued, forty-year rest) in language that credits the LORD implicitly ('Midian was subdued *before* the sons of Israel') but names Gideon explicitly as the era's marker ('in the days of Gideon'). The peace is personal, not structural. It has no covenantal foundation deeper than the judge's continued presence.\n\nGideon's personal epilogue (8:29-32) is marked by an almost clinical accumulation of facts: he returned home (8:29), had seventy sons by many wives (8:30), had a concubine in Shechem who bore Abimelech (8:31), and died at a ripe old age (8:32). The narrator offers no verdict on the polygamy or the concubinage — except to name the concubine's son Abimelech, 'my father is king' (*avi-melekh*). The irony is brutal: Gideon refused to be king, but his son's name confesses that he was. And Abimelech will spend chapter 9 making the name true in the worst possible way, massacring his sixty-nine half-brothers on a stone.\n\nVerses 33-35 are the epilogue's sharpest lines. The apostasy returns 'as soon as' Gideon is dead — there is no mourning, no gradual drift, no generational distance. Baal-berith ('lord of the covenant,' a Shechemite deity) becomes their god (8:33). The covenant with the LORD is replaced by a god whose very name appropriates covenant vocabulary. Then the narrator names the double ingratitude that defines Israel's failure: they did not remember the LORD who delivered them (8:34), and they showed no kindness (*chesed*) to Gideon's household (8:35). *Chesed* is the covenant's central relational word — loyal love, steadfast faithfulness. Israel owes *chesed* to Gideon's household as a reflection of what the LORD showed Israel through him. They render neither.\n\nThis is where the chapter ends — not with Gideon's legacy but with Israel's abandonment of it. The chapter that began with Ephraim demanding honor ends with Israel withholding the only honor that mattered: the memory of what the LORD had done through a weary man who was still pursuing."
